I am really curious about how you implemented the motion profile in your elevator and especially in the shooter hood (pinion system), because we had lots of issues with motion profiles in Neos. I think a lot of teams had similar issues because, as far as I know, Neoâ€™s internal motion control relies on velocity error rather than positional error, unlike CTRE â€™s motion control.

Thanks, Arda

posts.name: Emerson OHara
posts.cooked:
ArdaTurkmen:

implemented the motion profile in your elevator

For the elevator we use the WPILIB ElevatorFeedForward and Trapezoidal Profile classes not smart motion. If we were using a Kraken here we would use MotionMagic for sure.

ArdaTurkmen:

shooter hood (pinion system)

We actually just use a P value on this, but it should use a ArmFeedForward as well since it has a swinging CG. (we probably will fix this for next competition, or atleast add a kG/kS gain)

posts.name: Matt Golman

posts.name: Emerson OHara
posts.cooked:
Britt:

how fast are you running all the shafts that are using bushings and are you using any grease? did end up having to replace any of them throughout the season?

I believe most of our ratios are around 3:1 off the motors. So roughly 1500-2000 give or take. We did not need to replace any bushings, we greased them originally but once assembled to save time we would work oil in by rotating and moving the shaft axially (we left axial float on all shafts to reduce friction) then wipe off the excess afterwards, this kind of just helps aid the embedded oil.

We find the bushings to work pretty well once worn in and aligned, we made sure not to have them be tight press fits as that would cause the bushings to shrink and squeeze the rounded hex too much. We did develop a spherical bushing mount but decided we preferred the compactness so just worked to make sure shaft alignment was good when tightening down everything.

if you look at the routing here this might help, basically the motor/gearbox turns the big pulley at the bottom that causes the belt to move, since the carriage system is clamped to the belt, it moves up, once it hits the top of each stage the elevator has no choice but to move up until it is extended all of the way on the bearing block travel where the motor will stall with it fully extended (how we do the trap).
